Explain types of loss function with example
A loss function measures how much error exists between the predicted output and the actual output.
The goal of training is to minimize the loss.
Types of Loss Functions
Regression Loss Functions
Used when output is a continuous numerical value.
Mean Squared Error (MSE)
Used in Linear Regression.
MSE = \frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^{n}(y_i-\hat{y}_i)^2
Squares the error difference.
Large errors get higher penalty.
Example:
Actual Price = 20
Predicted Price = 18
Error = (20 - 18 = 2)
Squared Error = (2^2 = 4)
Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE)
RMSE = \sqrt{\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^{n}(y_i-\hat{y}_i)^2}
Square root of MSE.
Easier to interpret because unit remains same as output
Mean Absolute Error (MAE)
MAE = \frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^{n}|y_i-\hat{y}_i|
Uses absolute difference.
Less sensitive to outliers.
Example:
Actual = 10
Predicted = 7
Absolute Error = |10 − 7| = 3
Classification Loss Functions
Used when output belongs to categories/classes.
Binary Cross Entropy
Used for binary classification problems.
L=-\frac{1}{N}\sum_{i=1}^{N}[y_i\log(\hat{y}_i)+(1-y_i)\log(1-\hat{y}_i)]
Example:
Positive/Negative sentiment analysis
Spam email detection
Categorical Cross Entropy
Used for multiclass classification.
Example:
Classifying images into:
Cat
Dog
Bird
What are L1 and L2 loss functions?
L1 Loss Function (Least Absolute Error)
L1 loss calculates the absolute difference between actual and predicted values.
L1 = \sum |y-\hat{y}|
Characteristics:
Less sensitive to outliers
Produces sparse models
Used in Lasso Regression
Example:
Actual = 8
Predicted = 5
L1 Loss = |8 − 5| = 3
L2 Loss Function (Least Squared Error)
L2 loss calculates squared difference between actual and predicted values.
L2 = \sum (y-\hat{y})^2
Characteristics:
Penalizes large errors heavily
Sensitive to outliers
Used in Ridge Regression
Example:
Actual = 8
Predicted = 5
L2 Loss = (8 − 5)² = 9
Difference Between L1 and L2 Loss
Feature	L1 Loss	L2 Loss
Formula	Absolute Error	Squared Error
Outlier Sensitivity	Low	High
Sparsity	Yes	No
Regression Type	Lasso	Ridge

